1358","1316–Female":"1316–Deceased","1321–1366":"1321–1366","1325–1383":"1325–1383","1270–1366":"1270–1366","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1284":"1284","1383":"1383","1372":"1372","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1316":"1316","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","about 1316":"about 1316","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1366":"1366","1321":"1321","1342":"1342","about 1301":"about 1301","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales","Penhow, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Penhow, Monmouthshire, Wales","Undy near Newport and Penhow, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Penhow, Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Maur","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: nickname for someone supposedly resembling a mouse, in appearance or timidity, from Middle High German <i>mūs</i> ‘mouse’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from German <i>Maus</i> ‘mouse’, one of the most common of the unflattering surnames imposed on Jews by non-Jewish government officials in 18th- and 19th-century central Europe."],"variants":[{"name":"Muus","meanings":["German (Hamburg): nickname for someone supposedly resembling a mouse, in appearance or timidity, from Middle High German <i>mūs</i> ‘mouse’. Compare   Maus   and   Muhs  ."]},{"name":"Muske","meanings":["North German (also <b>Müske</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Middle Low German <i>mūs</i> ‘mouse’ (see   Maus   1)."]},{"name":"Mauss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Wilhelm.","German: variant of   Maus  ."]},{"name":"Meisel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Anatoliy, Boris, Leonid, Yefim.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Meisel  ."]},{"name":"Mousel","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Mäusl</b>, from a diminutive of   Maus  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger St Maur II was born in 1284, in Penhow, Monmouthshire, Wales, his father, Sir Roger Seymour de St. Maur, was 14 and his mother, Alice Lisle, was 14. He married Joan Dameral St Maur in 1300, in Penhow, Monmouthshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1342, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1284–1342":"1284–1342","1294–1372":"1294